00:09:07.880 --> 00:09:14.740
Okay. Today I will -- the topics
of discussion, the early history

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:19.460
of Prince Hall Masonry here in the
District of Columbia: 1822 to 1849,

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:23.170
I'm going to talk about the
antebellum period in the district,

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:26.490
1850 through 1862 specifically.

00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:32.120
The Civil War to Reconstruction,
1863 to 1880, and, finally,

00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:38.320
the post-reconstruction to the
turn of the century, 1880 to 1900.

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:43.210
The early -- early history
of Prince Hall Masonry, well,

00:09:43.210 --> 00:09:48.180
Prince Hall Masonry starts in
Washington D.C. officially in 1825.

00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:52.070
But before 1825, there were
some things that occurred,

00:09:52.070 --> 00:09:56.770
which caused the brothers
to turn to masonry

00:09:56.770 --> 00:09:58.850
as a way to solve their problems.

00:09:58.850 --> 00:10:02.600
When the federal government --
when the Constitution was written,

00:10:02.600 --> 00:10:05.360
it provided for the
creation of the District

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:07.870 position:56%
of Columbia for the federal capital.

00:10:07.870 --> 00:10:13.040
After the 10 mile square was laid
out, and the government moved

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:17.100
from Philadelphia to
Washington in 1800, what we --

00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:21.460
what they found were there were
some free African Americans living

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:24.290
within the borders of the
district, but there were no rules

00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:26.240
or laws which applied to them.

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:30.060
There were only rules or laws that
applied to those still in captivity

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:32.690
in the institution of slavery.

00:10:32.690 --> 00:10:37.260
But in 1816, a unique set of
experiences started to occur.

00:10:37.260 --> 00:10:41.850
The founding of the American
colonization society.

00:10:41.850 --> 00:10:47.350 position:56%
Now this was done because the --
the plantation owners, slave owners,

00:10:47.350 --> 00:10:52.340
had a problem with the
growing number of free Africans

00:10:52.340 --> 00:10:55.620
that were beginning to
live in the country,

00:10:55.620 --> 00:10:57.770
but there were no real
provisions for them.

00:10:57.770 --> 00:11:00.650
The same was true here in
the District of Columbia.

00:11:00.650 --> 00:11:03.970
So in 1816, they came up
with a plan, of course,

00:11:03.970 --> 00:11:07.160
of shipping all the free
blacks out of America.

00:11:07.160 --> 00:11:11.290
They -- they've got funding and
formed what we know as the Colony

00:11:11.290 --> 00:11:15.450
of Liberia on the west coast
of Africa, and set about trying

00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:17.540
to ship our free blacks to Liberia.

00:11:17.540 --> 00:11:24.700
In the District, in
1821, following the lead

00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:27.630
of the American colonization
society, the District Board

00:11:27.630 --> 00:11:32.960
of Aldermen passed what we called
the harshest set of black codes,

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:37.530
which limited -- limited the
ability of free blacks to move

00:11:37.530 --> 00:11:39.070
about in the District of Columbia,

00:11:39.070 --> 00:11:43.060
and that caused quite a
concern to many free blacks.

00:11:43.060 --> 00:11:50.260
So, in 1822, a man, John W. Prout,
a brother from Philadelphia,

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:53.120
called a meeting in his
house, in Georgetown,

00:11:53.120 --> 00:11:56.400
and they had about 20 brothers
who came to the meeting,

00:11:56.400 --> 00:12:03.150
and he made a plea to them that
they should form a masonic lodge.

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:07.870
And he used the example of what
the brothers had done in Boston,

00:12:07.870 --> 00:12:12.860 position:56%
Massachusetts as the reason why
they needed to form a masonic lodge.

00:12:12.860 --> 00:12:17.530
What he talked about was,
one, the men who formed the --

00:12:17.530 --> 00:12:20.830
who led the revolution, and who
were leading the government were

00:12:20.830 --> 00:12:22.820
mostly freemasons.

00:12:22.820 --> 00:12:29.030
Prince Hall, the founder of the
order, had found that he was able

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:35.100
to get citizenship status for
free blacks in Boston by writing

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:40.030
to the city council, having
quite freemasons on that council,

00:12:40.030 --> 00:12:42.170
and he found a listening ear.

00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:45.070
His first letter, you
can find it in the --

00:12:45.070 --> 00:12:48.910
a book entitled, Letters of
Prince Hall, to this council was

00:12:48.910 --> 00:12:53.990
to get permission to build a
school for the free black children

00:12:53.990 --> 00:12:56.240
of Boston, and that was granted.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:59.790
Later on, he wrote and asked for
permission to build a church,

00:12:59.790 --> 00:13:02.710
and later on, this lodge
wrote and asked for permission

00:13:02.710 --> 00:13:07.180
to build what we now know today as
The Historic African Meeting House.

00:13:07.180 --> 00:13:12.310
So, steps to citizenship
were achieved in Boston,

00:13:12.310 --> 00:13:15.100
which had not been
achieved anywhere else.

00:13:15.100 --> 00:13:23.810
In 18 -- in 1797, the same plan
was shipped to Philadelphia,

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:28.780
Pennsylvania, where Absalom
Jones and Richard Allen,

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:33.230
who had founded the first
black church in Philadelphia,

00:13:33.230 --> 00:13:38.700
came to Boston because they
were, again, suffering from some

00:13:38.700 --> 00:13:43.610 position:56%
of the same indignities because they
were not included in the legislation

00:13:43.610 --> 00:13:45.150
as citizens of Philadelphia.

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:48.040
So they wanted to reproduce the --

00:13:48.040 --> 00:13:50.800
what I call the Prince
Hall template,

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:53.210
to assert their rights
in Philadelphia.

00:13:53.210 --> 00:13:57.710
At that time, the government
itself was housed in Philadelphia,

00:13:57.710 --> 00:14:00.750
they didn't move to
Washington until 1800.

00:14:00.750 --> 00:14:04.490
So while -- while there, a
lot of the brothers who --

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:08.360
who became Prince Hall
masons started to interact

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:12.880
with those masons in the federal
government who helped them interact

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.640
with the members of the
Philadelphia legislature

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:20.710
and the Philadelphia City
Council, Pennsylvania legislature,

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:23.770
and the Philadelphia City
Council, to get some rights

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:25.910
for free blacks in Philadelphia.

00:14:25.910 --> 00:14:30.600 position:56%
John Prout, being from Philadelphia,
knew what had happened, therefore,

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:35.700
he called for the brothers meeting
in his house in Georgetown in 1822

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:38.470
to try to replicate the
Prince Hall plan here

00:14:38.470 --> 00:14:42.150
in the District of Columbia.

00:14:42.150 --> 00:14:47.500 position:56%
They wrote and asked for -- to start
a lodge, they got permission to do

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:51.510
so on June of 1825, social lodge --

00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:54.980
what we call social lodge
number one, was established here

00:14:54.980 --> 00:14:57.440
in the District of Columbia.

00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:01.260
Upon establishing the lodge in
the District, the brothers began

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:04.050
to take their case to
court for citizenship.

00:15:04.050 --> 00:15:07.810
The first of those actually took
place before the lodge was formed,

00:15:07.810 --> 00:15:11.690
and that's the case of
William Billy Costin.

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:15.720
Bill Costin became
the first secretary

00:15:15.720 --> 00:15:17.940
of social lodge number
one, but he, himself,

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:19.920
had a very interesting history.

00:15:19.920 --> 00:15:24.890
The black codes, which limited his
ability to move about the city,

00:15:24.890 --> 00:15:27.780
which prevented him from being
on the streets after 10 o'clock

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:31.040
at night, which prevented
him from assembling with more

00:15:31.040 --> 00:15:35.100
than two other black men on the
streets, he felt were an injustice

00:15:35.100 --> 00:15:38.070
to him, so he took
his case to court,

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:42.110
and a Judge William
Cranch heard the case,

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:48.290
and he ruled that Billy Costin was
grandfathered into conditions prior

00:15:48.290 --> 00:15:51.550
to the black codes being written,
and all other free blacks who lived

00:15:51.550 --> 00:15:55.700
in the District of Columbia were
not subject to the black codes

00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:58.900
since they were here before
the codes were written.

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:01.290
Another one of the members
of the social lodge, in fact,

00:16:01.290 --> 00:16:05.700
worked for Master John Prout
himself, was later accused

00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:10.790
of [pause] helping slaves to escape
from the Underground Railroad

00:16:10.790 --> 00:16:12.630
through the District of Columbia.

00:16:12.630 --> 00:16:16.620
He was a schoolteacher, he could
read and write, and he was accused

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:19.260
of forging passes for
free blacks passing

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:21.480
through the district to go north.

00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:25.740
From my reading of the
record, he was guilty.

00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:28.590
That was part of what
he did, in fact,

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.890
social lodge number one
was one of the stations

00:16:30.890 --> 00:16:33.790
of the Underground Railroad
through the District of Columbia.

