00:49:15.410 --> 00:49:19.270
So I was quite surprised to
find that a lot of the people

00:49:19.270 --> 00:49:21.100
who were already heroes of mine

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:24.080
from black history were
also [inaudible] masons.

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:27.140
And so, you know, so it was kind
of like a cross fertilization.

00:49:27.140 --> 00:49:32.230 position:56%
My background plus the masonic
records, my method of research added

00:49:32.230 --> 00:49:34.590
to Brother Roundtree's
method of research,

00:49:34.590 --> 00:49:37.860
it was definitely a
work of collaboration.

00:49:39.010 --> 00:49:40.810
Yes, ma'am?

00:49:40.810 --> 00:50:08.810
[ Inaudible Background Question ]

00:50:08.810 --> 00:50:16.390
Oh, yes! John T. Costin, as an
example, was personally responsible

00:50:16.390 --> 00:50:20.510
for uplifting blacks in Georgia.

00:50:20.510 --> 00:50:24.060
He left D.C. and was called a,
quote unquote "carpet bagger",

00:50:24.060 --> 00:50:27.280
but after -- after the
war, he went to Georgia,

00:50:27.280 --> 00:50:32.240
traveled all over the state
organizing black folks,

00:50:32.240 --> 00:50:36.940
both for the purpose of organizing
them to vote to get empowerment

00:50:36.940 --> 00:50:41.590
in that way, and also in community
meetings, teaching them how

00:50:41.590 --> 00:50:45.480
to organize their resources
for their own upliftment.

00:50:45.480 --> 00:50:51.390
Another gentleman,
Richard Howell Gleaves,

00:50:51.390 --> 00:50:57.840
who was a past national
grandmaster and from Philadelphia,

00:50:57.840 --> 00:51:00.170
Pennsylvania, went
to South Carolina.

00:51:00.170 --> 00:51:03.130
In fact, he was elected
the Lieutenant Governor

00:51:03.130 --> 00:51:05.650
of South Carolina during
the reconstruction era.

00:51:05.650 --> 00:51:08.550
He as from Philadelphia,
Pennsylvania, but he came back

00:51:08.550 --> 00:51:10.330
and settled down, became
a member of --

00:51:10.330 --> 00:51:15.030
of the our body in Washington
D.C., but his personal wealth

00:51:15.030 --> 00:51:17.770
and knowledge helped uplift the --

00:51:17.770 --> 00:51:23.800
I did it again, uplift the
brothers in South Carolina.

00:51:23.800 --> 00:51:29.720 position:56%
So there was a way that the people,
our knowledge and organizing skills,

00:51:29.720 --> 00:51:32.690 position:56%
went south to organize in the south,

00:51:32.690 --> 00:51:35.630
the newly-freed Africans
there, right?

00:51:35.630 --> 00:51:37.930 position:56%
To help them get their act together.

00:51:37.930 --> 00:51:42.180
Another thing that people might
not know, but both Absalom Jones

00:51:42.180 --> 00:51:45.540
and Richard Allen of the African
Methodist Episcopal Church,

00:51:45.540 --> 00:51:50.420
were both grandmasters of masonry
in the state of Pennsylvania,

00:51:50.420 --> 00:51:59.020
and they sent riding bishops into
the south to organize churches.

00:51:59.020 --> 00:52:03.470
The two elements of what makes a
community, where they organize men

00:52:03.470 --> 00:52:05.380
as masons, and the church.

00:52:05.380 --> 00:52:09.110
They was the anchor for spiritual
development, as such, right?

00:52:09.110 --> 00:52:12.850 position:56%
And, again, those ideas, [inaudible]
from [inaudible] masonry went

00:52:12.850 --> 00:52:17.280
to settle and help create the
successful communities of blacks

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:19.880
in the south following
the Civil War.

00:52:20.990 --> 00:52:22.790
Yes, sir?

00:52:22.790 --> 00:52:40.160
[ Inaudible Background Question ]

00:52:40.160 --> 00:52:48.500
Okay, well, because of the
grand lodge being here in 1867,

00:52:48.500 --> 00:52:51.300
I think when [inaudible] was
formed, that the -- the --

00:52:51.300 --> 00:52:58.330
those men who created the
institution depended on a lot

00:52:58.330 --> 00:53:01.110
of the -- the brothers
in [inaudible] masonry

00:53:01.110 --> 00:53:05.210
to help give them a way
and get them set up.

00:53:05.210 --> 00:53:10.770
Dr. Warfield, who set up Howard
University's Surgery Department,

00:53:10.770 --> 00:53:14.210
was also one of our grandmaster,
a grandmaster of masons, alright,

00:53:14.210 --> 00:53:15.910
here in the District of Columbia.

00:53:15.910 --> 00:53:18.710
I don't have a list
of all the professors,

00:53:18.710 --> 00:53:21.390
but there was always
a close relationship

00:53:21.390 --> 00:53:26.070
between our grand lodge
and [inaudible] Howard.

00:53:26.070 --> 00:53:37.470
In fact, from 1865 until 1925, if
you were an African American man

00:53:37.470 --> 00:53:41.800
in America, the highest social
status you could have was being a

00:53:41.800 --> 00:53:44.140
mason, being a [inaudible] mason.

00:53:44.140 --> 00:53:48.010
The reason I put that date and line
in there is because from 190 --

00:53:48.010 --> 00:53:53.020
from 1904 through 1925 is
the period of the creation

00:53:53.020 --> 00:53:58.970
of the Greek fraternities on
college campuses, and over time,

00:53:58.970 --> 00:54:03.730
even though each one of them used
our procedures and our handbooks

00:54:03.730 --> 00:54:09.600
to create their organizations, as
such, right, as one became educated

00:54:09.600 --> 00:54:16.550
through time, in the minds of some
people, being a [pause] Greek --

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:22.690
in a Greek fraternity was the
highest status than being a mason.

00:54:22.690 --> 00:54:26.280
But about, I would
say from 1920 to 19 --

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:30.750
well, until 2016, or until today,

00:54:30.750 --> 00:54:33.310
one of the most [inaudible]
statement that you can make is

00:54:33.310 --> 00:54:35.210
that you're a double brother.

00:54:35.210 --> 00:54:39.550
Now, double brothers are mason and
an omega or mason and an alpha,

00:54:39.550 --> 00:54:43.640
a mason and a cappa, or what
have you, but double brothers.

00:54:43.640 --> 00:54:47.680
So, [laughter], you know, it's
like we -- we created them, they --

00:54:47.680 --> 00:54:49.720
they've come back and we've joined.

00:54:49.720 --> 00:54:53.970
So we both have the -- the frater
-- the college fraternal order

00:54:53.970 --> 00:54:58.780
and [inaudible] masonry all have
the same goals for our communities.

00:54:58.780 --> 00:55:00.180
There's [inaudible]
in moving forward.

00:55:00.180 --> 00:55:05.030
Yes? That's the last...alright,
last question.

00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:06.830
Yes, sir?

00:55:06.830 --> 00:55:12.410
[ Inaudible Background Question ]

00:55:12.410 --> 00:55:22.240
Okay, well, I'll put it this way,
is the -- when the masons of --

00:55:22.240 --> 00:55:28.060
of the revolutionary period,
designed the documents,

00:55:28.060 --> 00:55:33.300
which are the foundation
of this country, in fact,

00:55:33.300 --> 00:55:37.400
13 out of the 39 men who created
the Constitution were masons.

00:55:37.400 --> 00:55:39.840
The first country in the world

00:55:39.840 --> 00:55:44.750
to have a constitution is the
United States, and the idea came

00:55:44.750 --> 00:55:48.060
from the fact that masonry was
run by Anderson's Constitution.

00:55:48.060 --> 00:55:52.000
And many of the elements in the
U.S. Constitution duplicate what's

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:53.960
in Anderson's Constitution.

00:55:53.960 --> 00:56:00.070
But the -- what we call America's
original sin, not just slavery,

00:56:00.070 --> 00:56:05.140
but the discrimination that slavery
caused, [inaudible] tenants say

00:56:05.140 --> 00:56:11.550
that in the country, that
all men are created equal.

00:56:11.550 --> 00:56:15.890 position:56%
The government didn't practice
that, and though freemasonry is a --

00:56:15.890 --> 00:56:19.220
is an organization itself, which
states that all men are brothers,

00:56:19.220 --> 00:56:22.100
so we don't -- we only deal
with each other based on what's

00:56:22.100 --> 00:56:26.200
in our hearts, in those days, these
three [phonetic] didn't do that.

00:56:26.200 --> 00:56:27.500
So there was discrimination.

00:56:27.500 --> 00:56:31.550
There were whites who wouldn't --
who didn't allow their interaction.

00:56:31.550 --> 00:56:35.700
My co-author wrote a piece several
years ago, called two faces,

00:56:35.700 --> 00:56:39.460
one public and one private,
in which -- which --

00:56:39.460 --> 00:56:44.230
what was pointed out is that there
have always been white masons

00:56:44.230 --> 00:56:48.710
who worked with and helped
black masons move forward.

00:56:48.710 --> 00:56:52.940
But at the same time, there
have always been white masons

00:56:52.940 --> 00:56:57.320
who did everything they could to
prevent us from moving anywhere,

00:56:57.320 --> 00:57:00.680
and who denied our
legitimacy, as such.

00:57:00.680 --> 00:57:02.950
Right? So that's internal politics.

00:57:02.950 --> 00:57:06.310
So, in America, as opposed to
anywhere else in the world,

00:57:06.310 --> 00:57:09.880
what's called [inaudible]
freemasonry is talked

00:57:09.880 --> 00:57:13.280
about as black freemasonry or
African American freemasonry.

00:57:13.280 --> 00:57:17.230
But the truth of the matter is
both groups practiced the exact

00:57:17.230 --> 00:57:18.860
same thing.

00:57:18.860 --> 00:57:20.160
Both groups do.

00:57:20.160 --> 00:57:21.870
But, again, the legacy of racism

00:57:21.870 --> 00:57:26.100
and discrimination has
-- is still with us.

00:57:26.100 --> 00:57:32.920 position:56%
There are -- of the 50 states in the
country, there are 8 grand lodge,

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:34.830
or white masons, primarily
in the south,

00:57:34.830 --> 00:57:37.120
who don't recognize
black freemasonry

00:57:37.120 --> 00:57:39.380
as a legitimate fraternal
organization.

00:57:39.380 --> 00:57:42.130
Therefore, when we talk, we
have to talk about white masonry

00:57:42.130 --> 00:57:45.610
and black masonry and we
bring up those circumstances.

00:57:45.610 --> 00:57:48.510
Okay? Well, thank you very much!

00:57:48.510 --> 00:57:54.680
