01:00:02.730 --> 01:00:07.570
And on a final note, my father
was a double brother [laughter].

01:00:07.570 --> 01:00:10.490
He left Howard, he was
drafted while he was a student

01:00:10.490 --> 01:00:14.550
at Howard University to go to
Tuskegee Army air-flying school

01:00:14.550 --> 01:00:18.470
as a Tuskegee airman, and while
he was in Tuskegee, Alabama,

01:00:18.470 --> 01:00:20.260
he became a Prince Hall mason.

01:00:20.260 --> 01:00:24.060
He went through Lewis Adams Lodge,
and for those of us who know,

01:00:24.060 --> 01:00:27.930
Lewis Adams was one of the
founders of Tuskegee Institute,

01:00:27.930 --> 01:00:31.440 position:56%
along with Booker T. Washington, and
so they named the lodge after him,

01:00:31.440 --> 01:00:33.580
and my father went
through that lodge,

01:00:33.580 --> 01:00:36.560
and one of the things
he has always told us is

01:00:36.560 --> 01:00:39.930
that to be a balanced black
person, you have to belong

01:00:39.930 --> 01:00:42.920
to the craft and to a fraternity.

01:00:42.920 --> 01:00:44.220
That's what he would say.

01:00:44.220 --> 01:00:48.800
He said, because there you get
the representation of all of us,

01:00:48.800 --> 01:00:52.350
and he said that Prince Hall
freemasonry was the gatekeeper

01:00:52.350 --> 01:00:54.440
of our culture, and you can hear

01:00:54.440 --> 01:00:57.690
from Tehuti's presentation
today how it is.

01:00:57.690 --> 01:01:00.980
You cannot tell the story of
African Americans in this country

01:01:00.980 --> 01:01:04.130
without telling the story
of Prince Hall freemasonry.

